
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `networkctl` baraye control va didan vaziat (status) network dar systemd estefade mishavad. Ba in dastoor, mitavanid etela'at raje' be interface-haye network, link-ha, va network configuration ra bebinid va anha ra modiriyat konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `networkctl status` --> 📝 Namayesh vaziat kolli network va hame interface-ha.
    🔹 `networkctl list`   --> 📜 List kardan hameye interface-haye network va vaziat anha.
    🔹 `networkctl show [interface]` --> 👀 Namayesh etela'at kamel dar mored yek interface khas. (be jaye [interface] name interface ra benevisid, mesl-e `eth0`).
    🔹 `networkctl renew [interface]` --> 🔄 Daryaft dobare address IP baraye yek interface az DHCP.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ networkctl status

    🔹 Namayesh vaziat kolli network system.

    $ networkctl list

    🔹 List kardan hameye interface-haye network.

    $ networkctl show eth0

    🔹 Namayesh etela'at kamel dar mored interface `eth0`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ networkctl status wlan0

    🔹 Namayesh vaziat interface wireless `wlan0`, mesl address IP, gateway, DNS server-ha.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `networkctl` command is used to control and view the status of network interfaces managed by systemd. It allows you to inspect and manage network configuration, links, and interfaces.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `networkctl status` --> 📝 Show the overall network status and all interfaces.
    🔹 `networkctl list`   --> 📜 List all network interfaces and their status.
    🔹 `networkctl show [interface]` --> 👀 Show detailed information about a specific interface. (Replace [interface] with the interface name, e.g., `eth0`).
    🔹 `networkctl renew [interface]` --> 🔄 Renew the IP address for an interface from DHCP.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ networkctl status

    🔹 Show the overall network status of the system.

    $ networkctl list

    🔹 List all network interfaces.

    $ networkctl show eth0

    🔹 Show detailed information about the `eth0` interface.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ networkctl status wlan0

    🔹 Display the status of the wireless interface `wlan0`, including IP address, gateway, and DNS servers.
